Because \nabla  f is Lipschitz, by 1st-order Taylor approximation

f(\mathbf {x}^{\prime })\leq  f(\mathbf {x})+\langle \nabla  f(\mathbf {x}),\mathbf {x}^{\prime }-\mathbf {x}\rangle +\frac {L}{2}\left ||\mathbf {x}^{\prime }-\mathbf {x}\right ||_{2}^{2},\quad \forall \ \mathbf {x}^{\prime },\mathbf {x}
Now take \mathbf {x}' = \mathbf {x} - \tau  \nabla  f( \mathbf {x}). Then
   \begin {align*}     f(\mathbf {x}^{\prime }) &\leq  f(\mathbf {x})+ \tau  ||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x} )||_2^2 + \frac {\tau ^2 L}{2} ||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2 \\     &= f( \mathbf {x}) - \tau (1 - \frac {\tau  L}{2})||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2   \end {align*} 
  Take \tau  = \frac {1}{L}, such that
     \begin {align*} f( \mathbf {x}) - \tau (1 - \frac {\tau  L}{2})||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2 &= f( \mathbf {x}) - \frac {1}{2L}||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2     \end {align*}

Because \nabla  f is Lipschitz, by 1st-order Taylor approximation

f(\mathbf {x}^{\prime })\leq  f(\mathbf {x})+\langle \nabla  f(\mathbf {x}),\mathbf {x}^{\prime }-\mathbf {x}\rangle +\frac {L}{2}\left ||\mathbf {x}^{\prime }-\mathbf {x}\right ||_{2}^{2},\quad \forall \ \mathbf {x}^{\prime },\mathbf {x}
Now take \mathbf {x}' = \mathbf {x} - \tau  \nabla  f( \mathbf {x}). Then
   \begin {align*}     f(\mathbf {x}^{\prime }) &\leq  f(\mathbf {x})+ \tau  ||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x} )||_2^2 + \frac {\tau ^2 L}{2} ||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2 \\     &= f( \mathbf {x}) - \tau (1 - \frac {\tau  L}{2})||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2   \end {align*} 
  Take \tau  = \frac {1}{L}, such that
     \begin {align*} f( \mathbf {x}) - \tau (1 - \frac {\tau  L}{2})||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2 &= f( \mathbf {x}) - \frac {1}{2L}||\nabla  f( \mathbf {x})||_2^2     \end {align*}
